=========================================
C++17 FOLD EXPRESSIONS
INTERVIEW NOTES
=========================================

1. What are Fold Expressions?

Fold expressions are a C++17 feature that simplifies working with variadic templates.

They allow you to apply an operator (+, *, &&, ||, etc.) over a parameter pack in a very concise way.

-----------------------------------------

2. Why were Fold Expressions introduced?

Before C++17, variadic template code was complex and recursive.

Example (Before C++17)

template<typename T>
T sum(T a)
{
    return a;
}

template<typename T, typename... Args>
T sum(T first, Args... args)
{
    return first + sum(args...);
}

Problems:

• Recursive template calls
• Hard to read
• More boilerplate
• Hard to maintain

-----------------------------------------

3. C++17 Solution (Fold Expression)

template<typename... Args>
auto sum(Args... args)
{
    return (... + args);
}

-----------------------------------------

4. What does (... + args) mean?

This is a unary left fold.

It expands like:

sum(1,2,3,4)

becomes:

(((1 + 2) + 3) + 4)

-----------------------------------------

5. Types of Fold Expressions

C++17 supports 4 types of folds:

-----------------------------------------

A) Unary Left Fold

( ... op pack )

Example:

(... + args)

Expands to:

(((a + b) + c) + d)

-----------------------------------------

B) Unary Right Fold

( pack op ... )

Example:

(args + ...)

Expands to:

(a + (b + (c + d)))

-----------------------------------------

C) Binary Left Fold

(init op ... op pack)

Example:

(0 + ... + args)

Expands to:

(((0 + a) + b) + c)

-----------------------------------------

D) Binary Right Fold

(pack op ... op init)

Example:

(args + ... + 0)

Expands to:

(a + (b + (c + 0)))

-----------------------------------------

6. Example: Sum

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

template<typename... Args>
auto sum(Args... args)
{
    return (... + args);
}

int main()
{
    cout << sum(1,2,3,4);
}

Output

10

-----------------------------------------

7. Example: Multiplication

template<typename... Args>
auto multiply(Args... args)
{
    return (... * args);
}

multiply(2,3,4);

Output

24

-----------------------------------------

8. Example: Logical AND

template<typename... Args>
bool allTrue(Args... args)
{
    return (... && args);
}

allTrue(true, true, false);

Output

false

-----------------------------------------

9. Example: Print all values

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

template<typename... Args>
void print(Args... args)
{
    (cout << ... << args);
}

int main()
{
    print(1,2,3);
}

Output

123

-----------------------------------------

10. Why are fold expressions powerful?

• Replace recursive templates
• Very compact syntax
• Faster compile-time evaluation
• Easier to read and maintain

-----------------------------------------

11. Where are fold expressions used?

• Logging frameworks
• Mathematical libraries
• Variadic utilities
• STL implementations
• Generic programming
• Parameter forwarding

-----------------------------------------

12. Important Edge Cases

Empty parameter pack is NOT allowed for unary fold.

Example:

(... + args)

If args is empty → compilation error

Solution:

Use binary fold with identity value

Example:

(0 + ... + args)

-----------------------------------------

13. Interview Questions

Q. What are fold expressions?

Answer

Fold expressions are a C++17 feature that applies a binary operator to a parameter pack in a concise way, 
eliminating the need for recursive variadic templates.

-----------------------------------------

Q. Which C++ version introduced fold expressions?

Answer

C++17

-----------------------------------------

Q. What problem do they solve?

Answer

They remove the need for recursive variadic templates by providing a simple syntax to operate on parameter packs.

-----------------------------------------

Q. What are types of fold expressions?

Answer

• Unary left fold
• Unary right fold
• Binary left fold
• Binary right fold

-----------------------------------------

Q. Example of fold expression?

Answer

(... + args)

